# Assign vowel roundness categories based on vowel type

# Assign vowel height categories based on vowel type

Warning: Unknown or uninitialised column: `prelex_vwl_hgt`.

df$prelex_vwl_hgt[df$art_vwl_nucl %in% c("aop", "cop")] <- "low"

# Filter out rows with NA values in prelex_vwl_hgt column

# Create new columns for feature differences
df$F1_F0 <- df$F1 - df$F0

df$F1_F2 <- (df$F1 + df$F0) / 2
df$F3_F2 <- df$F3 - df$F2
df$F4_F3 <- df$F4 - df$F3

# Convert categorical variables to factors
df$prelex_vwl_hgt <- as.factor(df$prelex_vwl_hgt)

df$AGE <- as.factor(df$AGE)

# Select relevant columns for modeling

data_for_RQ2 <- df %>%

2. Statistical analysis 🧐

2.1. Vowel height analysis

2.1.1. Data Preparation and Splitting 🔄

# 🏷️ Initialize LabelEncoder
label_encoder = LabelEncoder()

# 📂 Load the data
data = r.data_for_RQ1

# 🔄 Convert string vectors to numerical values
# This is necessary because machine learning algorithms typically work with numerical data
data['CHILD'] = label_encoder.fit_transform(data['CHILD'])
data['AGE'] = label_encoder.fit_transform(data['AGE'])

# ✂️ Split the data into features (X) and target (y)
# 'X' contains all the features used for prediction
# 'y' is the target variable we want to predict
X = data.drop('prelex_vwl_hgt', axis=1)  # Features
y = data['prelex_vwl_hgt']  # Target

# 🧪 Split the data into training and test sets
# test_size=0.2 means 20% of the data will be used for testing
# This helps to evaluate the model's performance on unseen data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, stratify=y, random_state=42)

2.1.2. Model Training and Hyperparameter Tuning 🤖

# 🔧 Define the parameter distribution for hyperparameter tuning
param_dist = {'n_estimators': np.round(np.exp(np.arange(1, 11, 0.5))).astype(int),
 'max_features': ["sqrt"]}

# 🌲 Create a random forest classifier
rf = BalancedRandomForestClassifier()

# 🔍 Initialize GridSearchCV with the random forest classifier, parameter grid, and other options
grid_search = GridSearchCV(rf, param_grid=param_dist, cv=StratifiedKFold(n_splits=10), scoring='f1_macro', verbose=2)

# 💾 Save the GridSearchCV object to a file
joblib.dump(grid_search, 'grid_search_object_hgt.pkl')

# 🔧 Fit the GridSearchCV object to the data
grid_search_result = grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

# 💾 Save the fitted GridSearchCV object to a file
joblib.dump(grid_search_result, 'grid_search_result_up_to_F3_hgt.pkl')

2.1.3. Load and Evaluate Best Model 🌟

# 💾 Load the GridSearchCV result object from the file
grid_search = joblib.load('grid_search_result_up_to_F3_hgt.pkl')

# 🌟 Create a variable for the best model
best_rf = grid_search.best_estimator_

# 💾 Save the best model to a file
joblib.dump(best_rf, 'best_rf_object_hgt.pkl')

# 💾 Load the best model from the file
best_rf = joblib.load('best_rf_object_hgt.pkl')

# 🖨️ Print the best hyperparameters
print('Best hyperparameters:', grid_search.best_params_)

2.1.4. Predictions and Evaluation 📊

# 🎯 Generate predictions with the best model
y_pred = best_rf.predict(X_test)

# 💾 Save the predictions to a file
joblib.dump(y_pred, 'best_rf_pred_hgt.pkl')

# 📊 Create the confusion matrix
cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)

labels=["low","mid","high"]
# Create a normalized confusion matrix
cm_normalized = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred, normalize='true', labels=labels)

# Create the confusion matrix display object with the labels
cm_display = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix=cm_normalized, display_labels=labels)

cm_display.plot(cmap='Blues', values_format='.2f')
plt.title('Normalized Confusion Matrix')
plt.savefig('confusion_matrix_up_to_F3_hgt.png')


# 📈 Create a series containing feature importances from the model
# Feature importances show which features contributed most to the predictions.
feature_importances = pd.Series(best_rf.feature_importances_, index=X_train.columns).sort_values(ascending=False)

# 💾 Save the feature importances to a CSV file
feature_importances.to_csv('feature_importances_up_to_F3_hgt.csv')

2.1.5. Data vizualization 🎨

# 📊 Import feature importance data
feature_importances_hgt <- read.csv("feature_importances_up_to_F3_hgt.csv")

# 📊 Rename columns for clarity
colnames(feature_importances_hgt) <- c("Variable", "Importance")

# 📊 Reorder variables by importance
feature_importances_hgt <- feature_importances_hgt %>%
    mutate(  # Reorder the Variable column by Importance
    Variable = case_when(
      Variable == "F3_F2" ~ "F3-F2",
      Variable == "F1_F0" ~ "F1-F0",
      Variable == "F2_F1" ~ "F2-F1",
      Variable == "F1_F2" ~ "(F1+F2)/2",
      Variable == "CHILD" ~ "Child",
      Variable == "AGE" ~ "Age",
      TRUE ~ as.character(Variable)  # Keep the original name for other values
    )
  ) %>% 
    mutate(Variable = reorder(Variable, Importance))

# 📊 Create a ggplot to visualize variable importances
plot <- ggplot(feature_importances_hgt, aes(x = Importance, y = Variable)) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, linetype = "dotted", color = "black") +
  labs(x = "Variable Importances", y = "Predictors", title = "Vowel Height") +
  scale_color_identity() +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text = element_text(size = 12),
    axis.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
    plot.title = element_text(size = 16, face = "bold"),
    strip.text = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(family = "mono"),
    axis.ticks = element_line(linetype = "blank"),
    panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "gray80"),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),  # Removed minor grid lines for clarity
    plot.margin = margin(10, 10, 10, 10)  # Adjusted margins as needed
  )

# 📊 Save the ggplot to a file
ggsave("variable_importance_plot_up_to_F3_hgt.png", plot)

      TRUE ~ as.character(Variable)  # Keep the original name for other values
    )
  ) %>% 
    mutate(Variable = reorder(Variable, Importance))
